  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the absence of citations and online discourse metrics, \"The Hybrid Practitioner,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2022, shows a noteworthy commercial presence on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads. The work maintains a significant academic role in the interdisciplinary discussion of sustainability and policy, reflected by its connection to one of the Sustainable Development Goals.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"The Hybrid Practitioner,\" released in 2022 by Leuven University Press, occupies a unique niche within the realms of sustainability and interdisciplinary practices. While it has yet to garner citations, its presence on commercial platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads indicates a potential for broader engagement with audiences beyond academia. This commercial linkage can be seen as an early sign of interest in its subject matter, highlighting a promise for future uptake.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work demonstrates relevance to sustainability and policy issues, evidenced by its alignment with one Sustainable Development Goal. This factor suggests that while initial academic discourse may be limited, there is likely an underlying acknowledgement of its critical importance in today's global context.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the inferred strength of the work\u2019s potential for public discourse is underscored by its categorization as having active public relevance, with indications of at least two related events. These events could serve as platforms to engage wider audiences and stimulate ongoing discussions around the themes presented in the book.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, \"The Hybrid Practitioner\" is positioned within a significant context pertaining to sustainability and interdisciplinary practices. As it garners attention on commercial platforms and aligns with policy-relevant goals, the potential for increased engagement\u2014both academically and publicly\u2014remains on the horizon.</p>",
